      "type": "html",
      "text": " Fail-safety isn't a property of all databases; it's a property of certain RDBMS products <b>when maintained by one (or more) qualified database administrators</b>. The reason the data in an RDBMS is safe is because it runs on a big piece of redundant iron with [[Five Nines]] uptime, because the DBA staff does nightly backups and keeps copies on a different site, and because the vendor will fly in consultants to get things up and running again should all hell break loose. If you store your data on [[Microsoft Access]], it will be no safer against accidental clobbering or system failure than if stored in the [[Windows Registry]], in a [[Dot File]] in your home directory, or in a pickle jar. Nothing prevents \"OO serialization libraries\" from being implemented in a similarly robust fashion.''",
