            "text": " Careful, you're engaging in [[No True Scotsman]] by attempting to redefine a \"DBMS\" as a \"DBMS with [[Atomic Consistent Isolated Durable]] semantics\". Access may not be a <i>good</i> DBMS, but it is a DBMS. At any rate, are you suggesting that it is not possible to write an OO serialization management system (a mere \"library\" of any sort is insufficient to provide the \"D\" in ACID) which, if properly configured and administered, would provide an object-store with ACID semantics? There are certainly some difficulties with object systems, for sure - but they are more with the \"C\" criteria and not the \"D\" criteria. When the state is scattered all over the place, rather than confined within the database, insuring all invariants are satisfied is a nasty little problem. But avoiding data loss in the face of soft - and hard - failures is a problem with many known solutions; many of which don't involve a DBMS. Probably the best-known is called \"making backup copies\".",
